"""
som_btb — Tang Mega 60K SOM board-to-board (DF40) interface.

Three mating DF40HC(3.0)-...DS-0.4V(51) receptacles for the SOM plugs:
  C2399  = DF40HC(3.0)-100DS-0.4V(51)  (SOM plug C2399)
  C2400  = DF40HC(3.0)-100DS-0.4V(51)  (SOM plug C2400)
  BTB9900= DF40HC(3.0)-80DS-0.4V(51)   (SOM plug BTB9900)

Signal nets are named after the physical PG484A ball (`SOM_<ball>`, e.g. SOM_Y14) or,
where the pin has a fixed role, after that role (SOM_DONE/SOM_READY, SOM_ADCTN...). These
names are DIE-INVARIANT on purpose: the ball is the same physical BTB pin on both the
GW5AT-60 and GW5AST-138, but the bank number and IO-function DIFFER per die -- so those
live only in each pin's comment (`# <ball>: 60K BANKn/func | 138K BANKm/func`), never in
the net identity. Full table + regeneration source: docs/btb_som_pinmap.md (from the Gowin
device JSON); cross-die upgrade check: tools/pinmap_crossdie.py. Shared rails: GND, P5V,
per-bank VCCIO (now io() PORTS -- the top-level owns them). WIRED: all 190 signal balls are
exposed as optional io() ports via _ball(); the top-level drives functional nets (SDRAM / HSPI
/ Apple bus / JTAG-UART) onto the ~168 in use, leaving the rest (SerDes Q0/Q1, spares) on their
ball-named local nets. Only the 4 dedicated ADC pins stay plain Net(). som_btb is now a pure
breakout -- future wiring just adds top-level connections; this file needs no structural edits.

NOTE: footprint = DF40C-...DS land pattern (identical pads to the HC(3.0) variant;
only the 3.0mm stack height differs). Pins marked *_RSVD / VCCIO_138B5 need a final
check against the SOM mechanical spec.
"""

DF40_100 = Module("../components/HRS_Hirose/DF40C-100DS-0_4V_51/DF40C-100DS-0_4V_51.zen")
DF40_80 = Module("../components/HRS_Hirose/DF40C-80DS-0_4V_51/DF40C-80DS-0_4V_51.zen")
MountingHole = Module("@stdlib/generics/MountingHole.zen")

# --- SOM mounting holes: 4x M2 (Ø2.15mm) on a 41.00 x 31.00 mm rectangle, per the Tang Mega
# 60K/138K SOM mechanical drawing (04_Mechanical_drawing/Tang_Mega_138K_60K_SOM.pdf).
# These live HERE, not in mechanical.zen, on purpose: they are the mechanical half of the SOM
# mating interface and must stay registered to CN1/CN2/CN3 (the hole-rect centre IS the SOM
# datum both are placed from -- see tools/floorplan_seed.py). The Zener sync groups footprints
# BY SHEET, so declaring them in mechanical.zen put them in a different KiCad group from the
# connectors they are rigidly tied to; same sheet -> same group -> they stage and move as one
# constellation. Mechanical (unplated) so the standoffs add no ground paths, per the
# single-star-point grounding decision (docs/board_floorplan.md).
MountingHole(name="MH_TL", diameter="M2", plating="Mechanical")
MountingHole(name="MH_TR", diameter="M2", plating="Mechanical")
MountingHole(name="MH_BL", diameter="M2", plating="Mechanical")
MountingHole(name="MH_BR", diameter="M2", plating="Mechanical")

# --- shared power / ground rails on the BTB ---
GND = io("GND", Ground)
P5V = io("P5V", Power)  # VBUS_SOM 5V feed from the carrier
VCCIO_1_2 = io("VCCIO_1_2", Power)  # bank 1&2 VCCIO (3.3V)
VCCIO_4_5 = io("VCCIO_4_5", Power)  # bank 4&5 VCCIO (3.3V)
VCCIO_6_7_8 = io("VCCIO_6_7_8", Power)  # bank 6/7/8 VCCIO (3.3V)
# VCCIO_138B5 (C2400 P67): voltage UNRESOLVED -- named for 138K BANK5 but the 60K neighbours
# on C2400 are BANK9 (1.5V I/O). No pilot signal uses it (SDRAM1 is all BANK6/7/8 = 3.3V), so it
# stays an OPTIONAL port defaulting to a local placeholder rail. Resolve its voltage (3.3V vs 1.5V)
# from the SOM spec before tying it to a board rail or routing any BANK9 ball through it.
VCCIO_138B5 = io("VCCIO_138B5", Power, optional=True) or Power("VCCIO_138B5")


# --- balls wired this round are exposed as optional io() PORTS so the top-level can drive a
# functional net (SDRAM etc.) onto them. A ball the parent leaves unconnected falls back to
# its own ball-named local net -- identical to the pre-wiring netlist -- so the ~110 balls not
# yet wired are completely unaffected. Fan-out (HSPI / Apple bus / JTAG) just wraps more balls
# in _ball() and connects them at the top; som_btb never needs structural changes again. ---
def _ball(nm):
    return io(nm, Net, optional=True) or Net(nm)


